segments.text: We say that my experiences, even though I thought it was very, very tough coming from where I came from, was not as bad as a lot of the other guys had it.
And I think across the board, we had a lot of people that flunked out just due to the fact that they didn't have time to study or that emphasis.
I think
I think that back on that, I was fortunate enough to be class agent 10 years from my class.
And I've talked to Z and the guys, had many, many different reunions and many reunions I was involved in.
And hearing all their war stories, they're either telling a pretty high, wild type of freshman year.
But I think they probably did experience a lot more than I did.
Describe a typical class day.
You got up at what time?
Well, the whistle jock would come in.
We could say 630, 6 to 630, depending on what was happening.
We did not do like the Corps does now, get up in the morning and run.
There was none of this running.
I think the only running I ever did was intramurals.
I ran cross country for our outfit.
But we would get up, and the whistle jock, of course, would blow three times, the third time being fallout, usually at 20 minutes tail,
Maybe it was 10, 5, and then fallout.
I'm not sure whether it was 20 or 10 minute, the first warning.
But anyway, we would fall out, and then we would be outside.
We'd stand formation, and the sophomores would check us over, and the juniors would be
then taking the formation, and then the seniors would come out of the dorm a little bit later.

Lots of times we'd be marching back and forth, but when the juniors took over, the first sergeant usually would at that time give us some type of instruction, and that's something in the 17 years that I worked in the commandant's office is something I always felt that was very important, but it had gone away, you know.
It was a good time for
One of the biggest problems, I think, in the Corps was lack of communications.
And even then, but even to this day.
Now, you had classes beginning at 8?
8 o'clock.
And I remember we would march to formation.
But that year, I was in dorm two, so we ate in Duncan.
Again, we would have the typical old days of you'd have a hot corner, a freshman be on hot corner.
We'd usually have two sophomores on the table and a junior.
In our case, since we had so many freshmen, we might have a senior which would turn, but we only had three seniors in our outfit.
When you figure you had 70-something freshmen and only three seniors, that's unbelievable.
And all three of them were in vet school, so...
One of them was married, so we only had two in the dorm, so it was different than the other units.
Colonel Scott was our TAC officer, referred to as the Goose.
And I've had a lot of experience with him.
And I asked him one time about, he was teaching math at Snook, and I asked him to talk
at our reunion.
When he come to our mini reunion, this was right before he passed away, and it put me on a real guilt trip because he said, are they going to throw those darn biscuits at me again?
Which was kind of customary.
Once or twice a year on the third Wildcat, everybody would chunk, as we would say, a deal or a roll at the
duty officer or the bull, the military officer, usually a reservist, sitting over at this little table with the OD.
the cadet officer of the day, who just happened to disappear at that time for some reason.
Who gave the signal to actually do that?
How did y'all, how was that organized?
It was usually done without Corps staff knowing about it.
Would y'all have planned it?
Oh, we would.
Somehow the word would have gotten around, today we're going to do it, and in the mess hall the word kind of got around to everybody on the third Wildcat deal,

and it just somebody started it and then of course uh a corps commander whoever was involved would uh or in charge that day would have to go see now could the biscuit or the the bread have anything on it or in it uh i'm from all the reports i've heard some of them did but again i don't uh
remember.
And that didn't happen but maybe once a year.
And then, of course, you pay the price.
Something's going to happen, you know.
What normally did happen?
Well, you know, you would, our, we might end up having an extra drill or we'd have inspections.
And that was one of the problems about the A&M that first year.
We drilled on Saturday.
which means if you were an Army unit, we had an armory downstairs, or really what it was was a dormitory room with bars on it and extra locks on the door.

And you would draw or get issued your weapon, which in that case we had M1 rifles on Friday night, and then you would have to clean them and everything, and then your room would have to be ready for inspection.
And so I can always remember in our dorm, Friday afternoon,

at 4.30 was usually the time to wax the halls, and that was freshman privilege, and so we would wax all, but Saturday we'd have the drill, and then we'd have to check our weapons back in, and well, it was always some junior that was called the armorer that would be responsible for taking them in, and then you'd have to
No matter what you did, it had too much oil or not enough oil.
And they could always find a junior that didn't have a car and wasn't going like Houston for the weekend or something.
Right now, on this class day, you had classes almost all morning.

All morning, and then back, we'd have formation at noon, we'd march the meals, we'd come back, and then that evening, formation, where we'd fall out for our retreat to take the flag down, and then again march, so we marched three meals.
During that time, though, probably most important time
for most of the units because your number one award was the General Moore.
And everybody thought they were going to win it
towards the end of the year, because everybody seemed like the upperclassmen kept you pumped up.
Intramural points participation was also something that was very, very important.
And so we would get out and we would practice, whether it was in the fall, flag football, later basketball.
We had tennis.
Ping pong counted just as much as football did.
So intramurals was a very, very big part.
And I remember that was of course something that was, sports was very important to me.
What happened in intramurals to that awkward kid who just wasn't very well coordinated?
Lots of times it,
It was basically terrible and sinful, because the upperclassmen would take the people that were actually the better athletes.
And those were ones in particular, because winning was much more important than participation.
So what it meant, it was kind of like the old days when you were playing out on the yard.
and you drew sticks or you flipped a coin or whatever to who goes first, and then I'll take you, you, you.
And usually that kid that's last is the kid that's last every time.
In this case, they would not be out there participating unless they were just really gung-ho.
And so you usually came up with teams.
But intramurals was probably the one thing that kept me at Texas A&M.
I remember my sophomore year, I became the athletic corporal and in junior year, the athletic sergeant.
And one little war story.

Richard Adams, who you know from Missouri, who is the dean of vet school, was on the elevator one day when I had been up having lunch with Mrs. Rutter coming down because she's a very close family friend with Sally's family and lived next to each other.
That's another story, but Richard had just been upstairs and it had been approved that he would be the dean of the vet school, and he was a freshman in my outfit when I was a junior.
And one of the first things he talked to me about was, did I know the year I left, and it took me five years to graduate, but did I know

the year i left that they won class a football championship now here is a gentleman a very distinguished professor but when he saw me he identified with intramurals and it was very very important to him and so we had a lot of fun a little humor you asked for some humor uh he told me the uh another uh another uh underclassman who i was with the entire times mike tatum who's also a

professor out in the vet school and he was a year behind me where Richard was two years and and Richard said when he became the dean he had walked the halls out there during the day trying to find Tatum so he could get even with him you know he wanted to have him do something now that he was in charge but but intramurals to answer your question
during the day was very, very important.
And lots of times we could miss evening formation and fall out late if we were participating, which meant we didn't have to before.
And maybe we'd have to go to sophomores holes, as they call it, and catch all kinds of hell for 30 minutes about our brass, not being there 15 minutes before we went outside and stood.
So if you participate in intramurals, you really got out of that.
Now, normally during the weekdays, about how much time did you have unscheduled?

if you were taking of course 17 hours you would you would probably find that you were in class let's just say you might have two to three hours because most people took 17 or 18 hours you'd have two to three hours at the max that you would have available during the day because again it gets back to what you've taken i was taking three courses that had labs so i was basically

involved somehow class all the time and then if you come back to the room the one problem our outfit did have was sophomores could come in your room and if you're there all of a sudden we got to make this spirit sign to hang up for the football game or we got to do this or that so academics was not stressed like I think
It is today.
Where did you and your closest buddies spend any non-scheduled time during the day?
I could have gone to the library, but I didn't.
I think I worried more.
more about going all the way over to Northgate for cleaning.
And I lived in Durham, too, or I was going to get something or just you don't know where the time went.
I know I did not take advantage of the library time.
I do know that my major problem was, as I mentioned before, that I had no idea how to study, period.
And I could sit there for the three-hour CQ at night
and procrastinate the whole time of, I don't know what I did, but I didn't know how to use my time wisely.
And then sometimes during the day it would be a panic to get that paper done or whatever, you know.

dining hall routine at your in your outfit was a little less stringent than in some of the others i i didn't think so at the time you know i thought really uh even up until when i graduated we had about as tough as everybody else but i have learned over the years being associated with a m i was fortunate to come back and
teach ROTC 70, 74, and nearly two years worked as assistant commandant for Colonel Parsons.
And you would visit with a lot more of your classmates then, and then I retired from the Army in 84 and came back, and then I was class agent 10 years, so I was deeply involved.

with what goes on at all reunions when people get back together and tell war stories of what they did, you start picking up a pattern that, yeah, a lot of these things happen to a lot of people, you know.
Did you all have cush questions?
Oh, yes, yes.
What were some cush questions?
I remember one little story of which, and a cush question, of course, being for dessert, and if you didn't answer it, you didn't get dessert.
But that wasn't the bad, it was the,
I think what bothered you was the challenge from those sophomores getting to you and getting over on you.
And I remember being asked a question one time, which class had the stone in their ring?
And I tried to find that answer.
And I finally, as I mentioned, this was the first semester, and I had already lost a lot of weight.
And I put more emphasis on this than I did trying to learn maybe the table of the chemistry.
But I went over.
Finally, somebody sent me to Mr.
Gay in the YMCA.
I went in and told Mr.
Gay I have this problem.
And it's really bothering me.
And so he just picks up the phone, dials down the hall.
He wants to talk to Earl Rutter, who was the vice president, come in to be vice president that year.
And all I could think was, oh, my God, those pissheads are going to kill me, General Rutter, you know.
And all Mr.
Gay asked him was that question, which class.
He could not remember, didn't know.
And he said, well, call Lupo.
Well, Mr.
Gay then called Mr. Lou, and Mr. Lou said class 30.
which if you check the course center or you check downstairs here in the former students, you'll see a class of 30 with a stone.
I found out later

little trivia about that that the the class of 30 had the option and some of them got the stone and some of them got the regular Aggie ring for that year caused a big big friction with their class and that was the last year that that they did it I remember one time and I
again, being associated with A&M and wearing a uniform for so long as I did up until 97 when I came over to the former students, you would meet a lot of people.
And a lot of these people were very distinguished former students.
But when they came back to your environment of the military, they wanted to live their military days again and talk about their experiences.
And I can remember Mr. Hal Booty here one time.
And we got to talking about that ring.

He got out the yearbook, which the 1930 yearbook is the most outstanding yearbook probably ever done because they were so far ahead, or he was so far ahead of his times with landing crafts out on the Pacific and aviation-type units or aircraft that just go on and on and on.
Even the cover where the one year from 1930, they had a covered wagon on the cover and

That year they had a city, and it was skyscrapers with lights on one side, and you'd go over to, I mean, the daytime on the other side, it would be at night, but you're familiar with that, I can tell.
But once we opened the Court Center, and I had talked to Randy Mattson about the possibility of us having another ring case over there, and he and Mr.
Williford was the president at that time, agreed to that.
And I got the Mothers Club from Houston to fund the case.

little sidelight on that we have a beautiful quilt there that the dallas mothers club did on traditions and it is just just really tremendous of the different traditions that patterns sewn in and and my sister did the army rotc one because her son was down here as a freshman that year but the houston mothers club jumped me out one time because i had a plaque there
It said the Dallas A&M Mothers Club, and they didn't have anything in the core center.
So the next thing I did was talk to the Houston Mothers Club and said, okay, we can have this ring case, and for $6,000 we can put your name on it.
They jumped on it, and where I'm leading up to now is one day we have a ring that comes in that's got a stone in it that says 1929.
which nothing tracked on this.
And found out that we checked to see that the gentleman that came in was a transfer student or referred to as a frog.
And he laid out a semester.
So he graduated with 30, but he was actually class 29.
So when he ordered his ring, instead of 30, they put the 29 on.
And that's also over in the core center.
I guess I've gotten off the subject a little bit from your question, but back to the Cush question.
Were there some that had no answer?
Oh, yes.
Well, I went back that night with the answer, Fish Henderson.
Yes, sir.
What class had the stone in their ring?
Mr. whoever it was, Fish Henderson requested permission to make a statement, sir.
I said yes and said, the class of 1930, sir.
And to this day, I can remember his reply.
That is correct, Fish Henderson.
Now for the second half of your question.
So yes, I didn't eat many calories that year, but it was not
Whether you got the question or not, or right, or the cush or anything, it became a little mind game with the upper class.
You didn't want them to get over on you.
You wanted to be a sharp freshman.
Sure, you had to memorize certain things.
I can tell you today, Alison Crooks Yates, first 13th last names on the Westgate Memorial, you know, and recognition, funded participation, agricultural, mechanical.
Those kind of things I remember.
the monuments, you know.
I'm still probably the keeper of monuments or things dealing with the military.
Anybody has a question, they seem to come to me instead of archives.
But the point is, questions we had, some of them were fair, some of them came out of Lupo's little book.
Since the standard now lists the questions you're supposed to know, because we were required to know all of the athletes, their hometown, you know, supposed to know what they're majoring in.
And then we had the unwritten rule of court trips, you go to the game.
Period.
You better go to the game.
Lord help you if you got back and you couldn't answer Monday morning which end of the stadium the Aggies came out of.
Did you and your buddies do any tricks, play any games at the dining hall table?
Only, the best I can remember, we only did them when directed by another upperclassman.
And a junior might have us do something to a junior.
And the way it would normally happen is the seniors would leave the dining hall first.
And then the juniors would leave.
The sophomores, you might have a horse's tail that'd stay around, a rashy, you know.
But most of the time, the games were played, you were directed, just like in the dorm, directed to play them against another upper class.
So that y'all very seldom used to... No, we didn't do any pull-outs there in the mess halls because you paid the price if you did, you know.
In hindsight, how would you describe the quality of dining hall food at A&M in your undergraduate years?
Well, I remember the cold cuts on Sunday.
I can remember that very well.
You know, Sunday night was a junior privilege to yell anything on the campus, you know.
And I can remember the cold cuts on Sunday night, and I can remember somebody yelling out the window about,

eight or nine o'clock and you could hear it all down the quad i hate this blankety blank place you know somebody just come back now most of my friends uh people i associate we hung around here on the weekends didn't go anywhere
And we'd go to DeWare Field House and usually play basketball or something at Saturday night, 2, 3 in the morning.
And I've set this tone that, thank goodness, both of my kids have done extremely well academically.
I'll give my wife credit for that.
But I was, again, involved.
If I had any free time, it was usually dealing with sports.
But did you not think the food was good?
I thought the food was excellent.
I mean, I really did.
Pardon me, except the cold cuts on Sunday night.
I thought one of the things I liked about it, though, was after the sophomores left, you could millhound.
You could go around and take anything off any of the tables.
And if there was something you really liked, you'd just go get it.
Because we ate family style.
You'd pick up the bowl.
And that was a freshman privilege, to stay and eat.
Unless you really had a problem, and the only problem we had was during football season when we'd have a yell practice in the Grove.

And after the second announcement, we all had to yell like hell and scream, hold your hands over your head and run out of there and run all the way to the Grove, you know, for yell practice so you could get chewed out and stand in detention some more.
But I always looked at it, everybody else having to do it.
Did you have a favorite main course or a favorite dessert?
Well, most of the time you didn't have dessert.
You know, you just, now we did, you could get dessert.
We had competition on march-ins.
Once a week or so they would, or maybe once every two weeks, we'd have judges or graders, as they're referred to then, and pick the outstanding outfits.
So we might vote

I mean, so we might bet with the medical company upstairs that we're going to do higher than they do, and then if we did, we got double cush, we'd get their cush, and then usually freshmen could have a cush.
We also had the inspections and formation, and the sharpest guy, if you were ever the sharpest guy, you might get a bag in or some kind of extra privilege, and your entire squad would get it.
And so I remember one time when...
We had a guy named Gerald Sullivan from Galveston, and we were going to, he was small, slender, and so we lived on the fourth floor, and his uniform was starched just like a razor blade.
Mike Shively was the best at fit shining shoes.
He shined his shoes.
Johnny Sullivan and I and our squad, we helped him down the stairs so he never did break that crease.
And we had him out there, and we worked hard on this.
This was important.
This was a big deal.
And that night, our squad won the privilege.
But we still laugh at this today because Robert Davidson didn't win, but Johnny Sullivan, his hometown buddy from Galveston, won.
And we lost a little faith in the system after that.

uh let's see uh jokes pranks good bull yeah there's a lot of a lot of that went on of course uh a lot of uh things we do the drowned outs and and i know that a lot of people probably told you about the drowned outs you know a real uh probably the start of my military experience would be uh uh the dorm across the way if uh if uh you were going to uh uh float it out as we'd say uh

on top of the toilets of course the little piece of metal we referred to as the head you could take that off but but you had to be in sync with whoever got in the steam tunnels and cut the water off so we would say at two o'clock in the morning
Nothing ever went at 2 o'clock in the morning.
It'd be 2.07.
You'd cut the water off in the steam tunnels.
The six cadets or eight or whatever was up there with their pipe wrenches with a hand towel of some sort so you didn't make any noise at all.
You'd take those heads off, and you'd have six, seven minutes to get out of the dorm.
And it would normally be the fourth floor because water would go down four stories.
And then the freshmen would be out of there, out of the dorm, because if, number one, if they came out and the water started, then it made it a little easier to track.
And so then you'd, of course, try to be back in your dorm sound asleep when the bulls or the
or the cadet officer of the day, or whoever.
And usually somebody would have seen a freshman running in a dorm.
You never could win.
It was one of those games that was played.
Most of the time, though, you're doing anything was because some upperclassmen had something coming.
And the old M-80s or cherry bombs wrapped in a Babbo can.
Another little military move, of course, would be, and I know you've heard this a zillion times, but is to one freshman would open the door.
Another one would pitch the, would light the firecracker, a babbo wrapped up with the M-80 fuse sticking out and pitch it in there.
And then the next one, because you had that delay, the next one would take a trash can.
Of course, I always had different names for everything.
And then you'd pitch the water on the one or two guys in the bunk.

and then and then you'd pull the door to in the end of a coke case you'd put that stick on the door and you'd slide her down where there's no way that door is going to open back in and you'd be long gone and but for some reason they could usually figure out who did it if you didn't if they didn't all the freshmen are going to stay up shining floors doing something but i will tell you that upperclassman's room was very very clean but when the sun came up you know
But there were lots of pranks.

I remember we had one guy who was a wildlife major and he had the bird nest out there on his balcony and it's amazing how you could let another freshman in the middle of the night from the window up above put ropes on them and
Put them down there and you can imagine what ended up in his little bird house there.
Just little off-the-wall things like that, you know.
But nothing what I'd call criminal or really.
Where was the entry place for the steam tunnels over in the Dunkin' Dining Hall area?
I don't know about the Dunkin' Dining.
Oh, but in our dorms, as you came in the two dorms in the middle of the dorm, the two doors, excuse me, right there, there was a door going down just like stairs going down into the basement.
In every dorm?
Mm-hmm.
Oh.
Yeah.
And same thing over in the old area where I lived the last three years.
And steam tunnels, it is sad because so many kids have gotten in trouble today over going down there.
And now the police have every kind of warning device.
And when you come out, you're going downtown.
This is an offense.
All right.
In your student days, let's make believe that you go down the steam tunnel in the Duncan area.
Mm-hmm.
How far under the campus could you or anybody else who knew the routine travel?
I can remember just going all through the area.
You could get up to Duncan and there'd be bars on there with a padlock, the bars being on some type of gate that would swing open.
So they had areas going into certain places blocked off, but you could actually go into steam tunnels and get over to other dorms as well as.
But if you were doing a float out or something, you know, most of those guys that's going to turn that water on,
They're going to, they could go that route, but most of the time you're probably going to come back up those stairs and go out that way.
But could you have gone?
All over the campus.
Really?
But now there is, and I haven't been down there, but I've read a couple of articles about the graffiti and everything that came along later.
I don't remember the graffiti, even though I spent a little bit of time in them.
What did...
people in your day used to light their way a cigarette lighter?
Flashlights.
We had flashlights.
Oh, I'm sorry.
Okay.
And describe the dimensions of the steam tower.
They were not very big.
I mean, there were some places, of course, you could stand up and walk, but there's other places that was pretty tight, and then pipes running through there.
How wide?
You know, it's amazing how everything was bigger back then in your memory, but it seems like it was about four feet wide is about what I remember.
Do you remember, and you were talking about good bull and pranks, do you remember any in class?
